<font color="#FF0000">CLINICAL THOUGHTS ON PTSD</font><br>
<tt>Thu Sep 18 18:38:55 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Congradulations, now you guys are talking. If you want the clinical i.e. text book breakdown on PTSD, I think it was posted months ago here, or possibly on tom's home page. Check local library for Diagnostic and Statistical Manuel IV, Manuel of Mental Disorders. Published by the American Psychiatric Association. It is the &quot;official&quot; book of labels and what it takes to have the condition. Reads like a chinese resturant menu mixed with the Readers Digest.  Some from column A, two from column B, with three add sleep disturbance, with 4 out of 5, add flashbacks, etc.  Warning, it is very &quot;dry&quot; and is a clinical textbook type of thing.<br><br>
There are some better books out there, but the key element to all PTSD is the talking, the sharing, about it.  The syndrome hinges on a &quot;experience that is unique and outside the realm of human experience&quot;.  How's that for a discription of the war in Nam?<br><br>
No 2 people handle it the same, and almost any experience that involves life endangering or threatening situations can, can, not always, can trigger it.  Usually heals it self with time IF acknowledged.  Can be chronic too.<br><br>
I once met a B 17 tail gunner from WWII who still was having nightmares and flashbacks over Nazi airplanes shooting at him.  That is a long and tough way to live, 50 years without a decent nights sleep.  Got some help, now he is fine.<br><br>
It has nothing to do with manliness, or manhood, or being a wimp or a victim.  At times the issue of control can be involved, but as I said, different things to different folks can cause it, and, my friends, it is very, very real.<br><br>
I wonder how many Post Office employee's have it &lt;g&gt; ?<br><br>
doc
